      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Debates Are Over. Now It's the Voters' Turn.</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert Nordvall letter deplores Gov George W Bush's and Vice Pres Al Gore's support of capital punishment in final presidential debate on October 18</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In the final debate, George W. Bush defended capital punishment solely on the ground that it deters killings, and Al Gore agreed that the death penalty is a deterrent to potential murderers (transcript, Oct. 18). The evidence that the death penalty deters crime is on the whole negative and at best (to those who support the deterrence rationale) inconclusive.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In the final debate, George W. Bush defended capital punishment solely on the ground that it deters killings, and Al Gore agreed that the death penalty is a deterrent to potential murderers (transcript, Oct. 18). The evidence that the death penalty deters crime is on the whole negative and at best (to those who support the deterrence rationale) inconclusive.</p>
        <p>Thus, scholars and criminal justice experts who support the death penalty simply don't talk much about deterrence. What a sad comment that our two main candidates for president support the death penalty on a ground that knowledgeable, thoughtful death-penalty supporters have abandoned.</p>
        <p>ROBERT NORDVALL  Gettysburg, Pa., Oct. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
